      <br>
      <p>The foundation for the brotherhood those 26 men started for the Missouri Chapter today remains uncompromised and stronger than ever with an alumni network of almost 1,000 alumni and an active chapter membership of over 100 brothers.</p>
      <p>Among the Missouri Chapter’s notable and distinguished alumni include Delta Chi’s National President the late and Honorable John Nick Gray; the longest serving Executive Director in Delta Chi History, the Honorable Ray Galbreth; the late Missouri Football Tiger Defensive End Jim “Cornbread” Martin, who’s play on the defensive line earned him Big 8 All Conference and All-American honors; MSNBC Executive Producer David Foster; Missouri Wrestling teammates Jim Jones and Don Godi, who are attributed as being the rebirth of the Missouri Wrestling program and ended their careers as varsity lettermen; former Missouri Student Association President Xavier Billingsley.  For a full list of the Delta Chi Fraternity’s distinguished and honored alumni, click here.</p>
      <p>The Missouri Chapter is currently residing in its fourth chapter house at 501 Turner Avenue. The original chapter house, a two-story brick structure, at 1415 University Avenue was home to the Delta Chi Fraternity from 1951 to 1966. It was in this home that time-treasured traditions of the Missouri chapter began such as the President’s Gavel pass ceremony and the Missouri Chapter Sweetheart position was created. Each year since 1951, young Sorority women will apply to be the Delta Chi Fraternity — Missouri Chapter Sweetheart. After a brief hiatus, the Delta Chi Fraternity moved into our second chapter house at 500 E. Rollins Street. In the Rollins Street house, Delta Chi’s invite-only Halloween parties became legendary and continue to be one of the best events of the fall semester.  The Missouri Chapter’s third chapter house from 1988 to 2009 was at 111 East Steward Road. The Missouri Chapter moved into the current structure at 501 Turner Avenue in 2011, where it has seen the chapter grow to over 100 members for the first time in chapter history; the election of one of our members as Interfraternity Council President, another first in chapter history.</p>
      <p>Throughout the Missouri Chapter’s storied history, young collegiate undergraduates have become men and where men have become leaders. Today, the Missouri Chapter boasts an extensive resume of campus involvement: the most Summer Welcome Leaders (New Student Orientation Leaders) of any Fraternity, Tour Team Members, Missouri Student Foundation, Homecoming Steering Committee, GAMMA Steering Committee, just to name a few. It is certainly an exciting time to be a Delta Chi at the University of Missouri as the members look forward to writing the next portion of the chapter’s history.</p>
      

