      <h1 class="page-header" id="phi">Philanthropy</h1>
      <p>The Missouri Chapter’s annual “Delta Chi For the Cure Week” philanthropy takes place in the closing weeks of the spring semester. The Internal Philanthropy committee chairmen plan all year to fundraise for the Delta Chi national philanthropy, The V Foundation for Cancer Research. The Missouri Chapter is proud to be a consistent $5,000 contributor for The V Foundation, but always hopes to increase our fundraising totals into the 10,000 range and above.</p> 
      <p>The V Foundation for Cancer Research, formed by ESPN and former NC State basketball coach Jim Valvano in 1993, has awarded more than $115 million to more than 120 facilities nationwide and proudly awards 100% of direct donations and net event proceeds to cancer research. After being diagnosed with cancer at the young age of 46, Jim Valvano dreamed of finding cures for cancer. Jim’s dream of finding a cure for cancer is one shared by millions. Although we have not yet achieved this goal, every day we get a little bit closer and will continue to honor his inspiring words, “Don’t Give Up . . . Don’t Ever Give Up!”</p>
      <p>During “For The Cure Week”, Delta Chis camp out on Lowry Mall in the center of campus and facilitate various fundraising programming such as a daily barbecue, penny wars and raffles. Past FTC Weeks have concluded with basketball tournaments, where members host and coach a bracket full of sorority competition. Our chapter is excited to announce that we will be holding our first annual FTC 5K race, beginning in spring of 2014. The FTC 5K will be held on Saturday, May 10th. To register, look out for a sign-up form on our Facebook page, “Delta Chi, Missouri Chapter.”</p>
      <p>In the fall, Delta Chi partners up with our local philanthropy, Ellis Fischel Cancer Center. In past semesters, brothers have also worked with with Second Chance, Special Olympics Missouri, Columbia Parks & Recreation and the Food Bank for Central and Northeast Missouri, to name a few. The Missouri Chapter always looks forward to serving new organizations and causes to instill in members the importance of giving back to the community.</p> 

      
      <h1 class="page-header" id="soc">Social</h1>
      <p>One of the top reasons why young men join a Fraternity is for the social experience and being a Delta Chi at the University of Missouri does not disappoint. </p>
      <p>From our exclusive invite-only date parties to socials with various sororities of Mizzou to Football Game Day tailgates, to our annual fall semi-formal and spring formal, and Mom’s and Dad’s Weekends, brothers enjoy the social experience year after year. Between social events sponsored by Delta Chi and invitations to attend various sorority date parties, Delta Chis have a very busy social schedule. Several brothers will tell you the social aspect of being a Delta Chi has enhanced their fraternity and their collegiate experience. </p>
      <p>Delta Chi hosts many different themed invite-only date parties throughout the year and invitations are always highly sought after from sorority women on campus. This gives brothers a chance to invite a guest or two and spend the evening socializing with their guests and their brothers. Date parties from the past have included 80s in Aspen, Take Me Out to the Ballgame, Halloween, a Christmas themed social called the Yuletide Ball, and Draft-A-Date (military themed social in honor of Veterans’ Day). </p> 
      <p>In addition to date parties, Delta Chi also hosts several socials with sororities at MU. A yearly social, Chi-ribbean, with the women of Chi Omega is always a highlight as it kicks off the fall semester and allows both the new members from Chi Omega and Delta Chi a chance to meet and experience their first college social. Other annual socials hosted by Delta Chi include St. Fratty’s Day (St. Patrick’s Day) and our Homecoming and Greek Week marriage parties with the sorority in our pairing.</p>
      <p>Before the Tigers kick-off at Faurot Field, one of the best spots to be in all of Columbia is the Delta Chi Fraternity house. Between the music, the good food provided generously by our alumni and their wives, the great atmosphere of friends and family, everyone leaves ready to go cheer our Tigers on to victory. You’ve never experience a football tailgate, until you have experienced a Delta Chi Football tailgate! <p>
      <p>During the fall semester, every Delta Chi anxiously awaits the arrival of semi-formal, known as the Red and Buff Ball. Each year for Red and Buff, the brothers and their guests go to various destinations outside of Columbia for a relaxing weekend away. Whether at the Lake of the Ozarks, Saint Louis, or Kansas City, the Fraternity Gentlemen of Delta Chi always have a good time during semi-formal, spending the night dancing with their dates. </p>
      <p>The hottest ticket in spring semester is a ticket to Delta Chi’s White Carnation Formal. This year the brothers and their guests will be attending the Kentucky Derby at historic Churchill Downs and be staying at an authentic antebellum hotel, The Campbell House. Formals of past years have been in Memphis, New Orleans, Kansas City, and the Lake of the Ozarks. Regardless of the destination, Delta Chi’s White Carnation Formal is one of the most talked about events throughout campus.</p>
      <p>Family members are also involved in the social experience of Delta Chi. Our annual Dad’s Weekend is held in the fall and allows for our fathers to meet, attend a football game together. Past activities for Dad’s Weekend have included a live comedy show at Déjà Vu, attending concerts at the Blue Note and a meeting of the Father’s Council of the Delta Chi Parent’s Organization. </p>
      <p>Don’t worry – we would never forget about the Mothers of Delta Chi members. Each spring, mothers journey from across the country to attend the Mom’s Weekend. Past events have included bowling at a local bowling alley, a fun and friendly trivia game called “Momma’s Boy,” visiting a local winery, and a meeting of the Mother’s Council of the Delta Chi Parent’s Organization. </p>
      <p>Delta Chi values leadership and academic success as its top priority, but its members also know how to reward the product of countless hours of effort, hence the extensive social calendar. </p>
